{{Cite sources|date=July 2024}} {{Ja_Pref_Route_Sign|pref=Tokyo|number=461|align=left}} [[File:Suijin ohashi.jpg|thumb|200px|View from Sumida Ward, Tokyo (January 2008)]] [[File:Midukamioohashi.jpg|thumb|200px|View of Suijin Ōhashi from the Shuto Expressway (August 2005)]] [[File:100 views edo 037.jpg|thumb|200px|Suijin no Watashi]]
'''Suijin Ōhashi''' (水神大橋) is a bridge spanning the {{ill|Sumida River|ja|隅田川|12=draft|12=draft}}, carrying a spur of the {{ill|Tokyo Metropolitan Route 461|ja|東京都道461号吾妻橋伊興町線|12=draft|12=draft}}. The western end of the bridge is located in {{ill|Minami-Senju|ja|南千住|12=draft|12=draft}} 8-chōme, Arakawa Ward, while the eastern end is in Tsuijidō 2-chōme, Sumida Ward. The bridge's name originates from the nearby {{ill|Sumidagawa Shrine (Suijin-gū)|ja|隅田川神社|12=draft|12=draft}}, also known as Suijin-gū.
The bridge was first constructed in March 1989 (Heisei 1). Its assembly was carried out on land, and the bridge girders were transported on barges to the site, where tidal changes were used to place them on the piers.
Nearby parks, {{ill|Shioiri Park|ja|汐入公園|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Higashi Shirahige Park|ja|東白鬚公園|12=draft|12=draft}}, serve as disaster response bases for Tokyo. As part of the disaster preparedness plan, Suijin Ōhashi was built alongside {{ill|Senju Shioiri Ōhashi Bridge|ja|千住汐入大橋|12=draft|12=draft}} to connect these parks. Initially a pedestrian-only bridge, it was opened to vehicular traffic on July 10, 1996 (Heisei 8), following the completion of the connecting roads.
On its eastern side, Suijin Ōhashi connects to the {{ill|Shuto Expressway Mukōjima Line|ja|首都高速6号向島線|12=draft|12=draft}} at the {{ill|Tsuijidō Entrance|ja|堤通出入口|12=draft|12=draft}}.
This location was historically home to the ferry crossing "{{ill|Suijin no Watashi|ja|水神の渡し|12=draft|12=draft}}."
== Bridge Specifications == * '''Type''': Steel road bridge * '''Structure''': Three-span continuous Nielsen-Lohse girder arch bridge * '''Length''': 157.0 meters * '''Main span''': 102.0 meters * '''Width''': 17.0 meters * '''Construction started''': 1984 (Shōwa 59) * '''Completed''': March 1989 (Heisei 1) * '''Project owner''': Tokyo Metropolitan Government * '''Design''': Tokyo Engineering * '''Girder fabrication''': {{ill|Mitsubishi Heavy Industries|ja|三菱重工業|12=draft|12=draft}}
== Public Transportation == * '''{{ill|Toei Bus|ja|都営バス|12=draft|12=draft}}''' ** {{ill|Route 40|ja|都営バス南千住営業所#錦40系統|12=draft|12=draft}}: {{ill|Minami-Senju Station|ja|南千住駅|12=draft|12=draft}} East Exit - Sumida 2-chōme - Shirahige Bridge - Higashi Mukōjima Hirokōji - {{ill|Tokyo Skytree Station|ja|とうきょうスカイツリー駅|12=draft|12=draft}} Front - {{ill|Kinshichō Station|ja|錦糸町駅|12=draft|12=draft}} Front
== Nearby Bridges == * {{ill|Sumida River|ja|隅田川|12=draft|12=draft}} : (Upstream) - {{ill|Sumida River Bridge (Tokyo Metro Hibiya Line)|ja|隅田川橋梁 (東京地下鉄日比谷線)|12=draft|12=draft}} - {{ill|Senju Shioiri Ōhashi Bridge|ja|千住汐入大橋|12=draft|12=draft}} * '''Suijin Ōhashi''' - {{ill|Shirahige Bridge|ja|白鬚橋|12=draft|12=draft}} - {{ill|Sakura Bridge (Tokyo)|ja|桜橋 (東京都)|12=draft|12=draft}} - (Downstream)
{{Sumida River Bridges}} {{commonscat|Suijin Great Bridge}} {{Coord|35|44|10|N|139|48|51|E|display=title|region:JP_type:landmark}}
}}
