'''Suijin Ōhashi''' (水神大橋) is a bridge spanning the {{ill|Sumida River|ja|隅田川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sumida River|qq=}}, carrying a spur of the {{ill|Tokyo Metropolitan Route 461|ja|東京都道461号吾妻橋伊興町線|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokyo Metropolitan Route 461|qq=}}. The western end of the bridge is located in {{ill|Minami-Senju|ja|南千住|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minami-Senju|qq=}} 8-chōme, Arakawa Ward, while the eastern end is in Tsuijidō 2-chōme, Sumida Ward. The bridge's name originates from the nearby {{ill|Sumidagawa Shrine (Suijin-gū)|ja|隅田川神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sumidagawa Shrine (Suijin-gū)|qq=}}, also known as Suijin-gū.
The bridge was first constructed in March 1989 (Heisei 1). Its assembly was carried out on land, and the bridge girders were transported on barges to the site, where tidal changes were used to place them on the piers.
Nearby parks, {{ill|Shioiri Park|ja|汐入公園|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shioiri Park|qq=}} and {{ill|Higashi Shirahige Park|ja|東白鬚公園|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Higashi Shirahige Park|qq=}}, serve as disaster response bases for Tokyo. As part of the disaster preparedness plan, Suijin Ōhashi was built alongside {{ill|Senju Shioiri Ōhashi Bridge|ja|千住汐入大橋|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senju Shioiri Ōhashi Bridge|qq=}} to connect these parks. Initially a pedestrian-only bridge, it was opened to vehicular traffic on July 10, 1996 (Heisei 8), following the completion of the connecting roads.
On its eastern side, Suijin Ōhashi connects to the {{ill|Shuto Expressway Mukōjima Line|ja|首都高速6号向島線|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shuto Expressway Mukōjima Line|qq=}} at the {{ill|Tsuijidō Entrance|ja|堤通出入口|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuijidō Entrance|qq=}}.
